Day_11 (Daily Problem)
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Question                                                                                                 (23-07-2021)
--------------
Recursion: Reverse a String

Write a function that reverses a string. Make your function recursive.



Examples

reverse("hello") ? "olleh"



reverse("world") ? "dlrow"



reverse("a") ? "a"



reverse("") ? ""

Notes

For non-base cases, your function must call itself at least once.

Check the Resources tab for info on recursion
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Solution 1:
-------------
#include<iostream>

#include<algorithm>

#include<string>



using namespace std;



int main(){

	string a;

	cout<<"Enter String:\n";

	cin>>a;

	

	string b=a;

	reverse(b.begin(),b.end());

	cout<<b;

}

Learnings:
------------
1. Used the reverse concept i learnt in Day_10.cpp
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Solution 2
--------------
//But we need recursion

#include<iostream>

#include<string>

using namespace std;



string reverse(string);

int main(){

	string b="Hello";

    cout<<reverse(b);	

}

string reverse(string a){



    if(a.length()==0){

    	return "";

	}

	else{

		return reverse(a.substr(1))+a[0];      

		

	}

}
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Flow:
----------
substr function in string library takes 2 args (initial pos of string , no of chars)

here we set the initial pos to 1 and no of char as null meaning 1.

using recursion we get first e then l then l then o and we reach ==0 so if statement is used

as recursion stores in stack so first o is returned then l then l then e. here recursion completes and next part

a[0] i.e first element is printed

Learnings:
----------------------

1.string library substr function.

2.flow of recursion

3.how return returns first part fully then nest part i.e a[0] here.
